|[[Inter Milan]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Inter Milan season|2017\u201318]]\n|36||2||0||1||0||0||colspan=\"3\"|\u2014||37||2||0\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Inter Milan season|2018\u201319]]\n|27||0||1||0||0||0||10||0||0||38||0||1\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Inter Milan season|2019\u201320]]\n|7||1||0||1||1||0||3||0||0||11||2||0\n|-\n!Total\n!80!!3!!1!!2!!1!!0!!13!!0!!0!!86!!4!!1\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Career totals\n!479!!38!!71!!39!!3!!1!!66!!4!!7!!585!!45!!79\n|}\n<div id=\"notes gs1\"></div><sup>1</sup><small>In West Bromwich Albion, includes [[FA Cup]] and [[Football League Cup]].</small>\n\n===International===\n{{updated|match played on 4 June 2011}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=27516|title=Borja Valero|publisher=European Football|accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Spain national football team|Spain]]\n|-\n|2011||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total||1||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Fiorentina'''\n*[[Coppa Italia]] runner-up: [[2013\u201314 Coppa Italia|2013\u201314]]<ref name=SW/>\n\n===International===\n'''Spain U-19'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]: [[2004 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2004]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/players/player=63946/profile/index.html|title=Borja Valero|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Don Bal\u00f3n Award|Spanish Player of the Year]]: 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/en/news/news/2014/three-key-viola-men-to-watch-out-for.php|title=Three key Viola men to watch out for|publisher=Juventus F.C|date=19 April 2015|accessdate=18 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Serie A Team of the Year]]: [[2012\u201313 Serie A|2012\u201313]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forzaitalianfootball.com/2014/01/gran-gala-del-calcio-2013-winners/|title=Gran Gala del Calcio 2013 \u2013 Winners|publisher=Forza Italian Football|date=January 2014|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Europa League]] squad of the season: [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League|2013\u201314]], [[2014\u201315 UEFA Europa League#Squad of the season|2014\u201315]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=2112220.html|title=UEFA Europa League squad of the season|publisher=UEFA|date=3 June 2015|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231222257/http://it.violachannel.tv/player_27794.html|date=31 December 2013|title=Fiorentina official profile}}\n*{{BDFutbol|4036}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Borja_Valero_Iglesias}}\n*{{NFT player|40180}}\n\n{{Inter Milan squad}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=navy\n|list1=\n{{2012\u201313 Serie A Team of the Year}}\n{{La Liga Player of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valero, Borja}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Madrilenian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid C footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid Castilla footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:Villarreal CF players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:ACF Fiorentina players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish footballer}}\n{{Spanish name|Valero|Iglesias}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Borja Valero\n| image = Borja Valero.JPG\n| image_size = 220\n| caption = Valero in action with [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] (2012)\n| fullname = Borja Valero Iglesias\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1985|1|12|df=y}}<ref name=Profile>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/borja-valero_prs207102/person.shtml|title=Borja Valero|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Madrid]], Spain<ref name=Profile/>\n| height = 1.74 m<ref name=Profile/>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Inter Milan]]\n| clubnumber = 20\n| youthyears1 = 1995\u20132004 | youthclubs1 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n| years1 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs1 = [[Real Madrid C]] | caps1 = | goals1 =\n| years2 = 2005\u20132007 | clubs2 = [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]] | caps2 = 77 | goals2 = 4\n| years3 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps3 = 34 | goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2008\u20132011 | clubs4 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] | caps4 = 31 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] (loan) | caps5 = 33 | goals5 = 5\n| years6 = 2010\u20132011 | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] (loan) | caps6 = 35 | goals6 = 3\n| years7 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs7 = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] | caps7 = 36 | goals7 = 5\n| years8 = 2012\u20132017 | clubs8 = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] | caps8 = 165 | goals8 = 14\n| years9 = 2017\u2013 | clubs9 = [[Inter Milan]] | caps9 = 80 | goals9 = 3\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132003 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain U17]] | nationalcaps1 = 15 | nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2003 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 3 | nationalgoals2 = 1\n| nationalyears3 = 2004 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps3 = 4 | nationalgoals3 = 2\n| nationalyears4 = 2011 | nationalteam4 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps4 = 1 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n| club-update = 09:06, 15 January 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Borja Valero Iglesias''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8bo\u027exa \u03b2a\u02c8le\u027eo}}; born 12 January 1985) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] for Italian club [[Inter Milan]].\n\nHe began his career with [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] but did not have any impact with its first team, and played for [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] and in England for [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] before joining [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in 2010. He also spent several years in [[Serie A]], with [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] and [[Inter Milan]].\n\nOver five seasons, Valero amassed [[La Liga]] totals of 139 games and 16 goals.\n\n==Club career==\n===Real Madrid===\nValero was born in [[Madrid]], and began his football career as a youngster in the ranks of [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcdm.es/entrevista-a-borja-valero/|title=Borja Valero: 'No me arrepiento de haber venido a Inglaterra'|trans-title=Borja Valero: 'I don't regret having come to England'|publisher=RCDM|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|last=Moy\u00e1|language=Spanish|date=10 March 2009|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> He made his first appearance for [[Real Madrid Castilla|the reserve side]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]], took part in [[2005 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|the playoffs]] to earn promotion and played two full seasons in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/2013/11/26/real-madrid/305872.html|title=La \u00faltima plantilla que descendi\u00f3 con el Castilla. \u00bfQu\u00e9 fue de ellos?|trans-title=The last squad to be relegated with Castilla. What happened to them?|publisher=[[Vavel]]|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|last=Balderas|language=Spanish|date=26 November 2013|accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nValero played only twice for the first team: given his debut by [[Fabio Capello]] against [[\u00c9cija Balompi\u00e9|\u00c9cija]] on 25 October 2006, replacing [[Javi Garc\u00eda]] after 60 minutes of a [[2006\u201307 Copa del Rey|match]] for the [[Copa del Rey]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2006/10/26/mas_futbol/1161844009_850215.html|title=\u00c9cija penetra en la galaxia|trans-title=\u00c9cija enters galaxy|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Juanma|last=Trueba|language=Spanish|date=26 October 2006|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref> he also featured once in the [[UEFA Champions League]], substituting [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Nieto]] in a 2\u20132 away draw with [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]] in [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League group stage|the group stage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertaddigital.com/deportes/ronaldo-salva-al-real-madrid-del-ridiculo-ante-el-dinamo-de-kiev-2-2-1276294311/|title=Ronaldo salva al Real Madrid del rid\u00edculo ante el Dinamo de Kiev (2\u20132)|trans-title=Ronaldo saves Real Madrid from ridicule against Dynamo Kiev (2\u20132)|publisher=Libertad Digital|language=Spanish|date=6 December 2006|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Mallorca===\nIn August 2007, Valero signed a five-year contract with [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] following his release from Real Madrid.<ref>{{cite web|title=Real starlet to join Mallorca|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11835/2409444/|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|first=Mark|last=Kendall|date=26 March 2007|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> He scored his first [[La Liga]] goals in a 7\u20131 home win over [[Recreativo de Huelva|Recreativo]] on 9 March 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=669076.html|title=Bar\u00e7a lose ground with Villarreal loss|publisher=UEFA|date=9 March 2008|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> and added another a month later, against his former team in a 1\u20131 home draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=679432.html|title=Ten-man Madrid held in Mallorca|publisher=UEFA|date=6 April 2008|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 May, Valero scored the first goal for Mallorca as they came back from 2\u20130 down to beat [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in [[Frank Rijkaard]]'s last home game as the latter's manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=226518&cc=5739|title=Barcelona 2\u20133 Mallorca|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=11 May 2008|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> He made 17 starts and played a total of 1,892 minutes during [[2007\u201308 La Liga|the season]], helping to a seventh-place finish.\n\nIn mid-August 2008, Mallorca's president stated that he had rejected bids from [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] for Valero and [[\u00d3scar Trejo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11698/3988591/|title=Mallorca reject Baggies' bid|publisher=Sky Sports|first=Francisco|last=Acedo|date=15 August 2008|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> but a week later, Valero signed for the latter \u2013 newly promoted to the [[Premier League]] \u2013 for a club record fee of [[Euro|\u20ac]]7&nbsp;million ([[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]4.7&nbsp;million). He agreed a four-year contract, with the option of a further year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~1372817,00.html|title=Baggies complete Valero capture|publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C|date=22 August 2008|accessdate=22 August 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828041306/http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~1372817,00.html|archive-date=28 August 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===West Bromwich Albion===\nValero made his debut four days later in Albion's 1\u20133 [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] defeat away to [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~46485,00.html|title=Hartlepool vs WBA|publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C|date=26 August 2008|accessdate=26 May 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227082546/http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~46485,00.html|archive-date=27 February 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Manager [[Tony Mowbray]] said that he would have benefited from his first game in English football, only hours after receiving international clearance, despite the defeat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11698/4057106/|title=Baggies' belief in Borja|publisher=Sky Sports|date=27 August 2008|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the team's relegation to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] after just [[2008\u201309 Premier League|one season]], Valero said that he intended to remain at the club: \"I still have a three-year contract here and would like to be true to that. For sure playing in the second division is not ideal. But if I have to put up with it then I am going to put up with it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11661/5351827/|title=Valero plans Baggies stay|publisher=Sky Sports|first=James|last=Dall|date=28 May 2009|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> By the beginning of [[2009\u201310 Football League|the next campaign]], however, he had changed his mind: \"I prefer to play in Mallorca and not to be in the second division in England. This is clear. I am disposed for a loan return but it is necessary for an accord between the clubs\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/5490045/|title=Valero seeks Mallorca return|publisher=Sky Sports|date=14 August 2009|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nJust hours before the close of the transfer window, Valero returned to Mallorca on loan for [[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/west-brom-borja-valero-returns-101853|title=West Brom: Borja Valero returns to Real Mallorca|newspaper=[[Birmingham Mail]]|date=1 September 2009|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> On 13 September, in the first match in his second spell, he scored their 1000th top level goal in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/09/13/1498616/villarreal-1-1-mallorca-borja-valero-snatches-point-for-the|title=Villarreal 1\u20131 Mallorca: Borja Valero snatches point for the islanders|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Paul|last=Macdonald|date=13 September 2009|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> In another away fixture, he netted in the last minute for the nine-man side to clinch a 1\u20131 draw against [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in October,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/275637?cc=5739|title=More misery for Madrid|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=24 October 2009|accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref> and was ever-present as they finished fifth and [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League|qualified]] for the [[UEFA Europa League]]; he also won the prestigious [[Don Bal\u00f3n Award]] for the best Spanish player in the Spanish League.<ref name=Bound>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11698/6252179/valero-bound-for-villarreal|title=Valero bound for Villarreal|publisher=Sky Sports|date=8 July 2010|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the campaign, Valero returned to his parent club after Mallorca confirmed they could not afford to take up the agreed fee of \u00a32.5&nbsp;million to make the move permanent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/6159059/|title=Valero set for Baggies return|publisher=Sky Sports|first=Francisco|last=Acedo|date=17 May 2010|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Villarreal===\nFor [[2010\u201311 La Liga|2010\u201311]], it was reported that Valero was joining Villarreal on a five-year contract,<ref name=Bound/> but the clubs eventually agreed on a season-long loan, with the move to be made permanent at the end of the campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/w/west_bromwich_albion/8800742.stm|title=West Brom's Borja Valero joins Villarreal on loan|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=19 July 2010|accessdate=28 September 2010}}</ref> He scored on his home debut, a 4\u20130 win against [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] on 12 September 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302038&cc=5739|title=Rossi grabs brace in Espanyol defeat|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=12 September 2010|accessdate=20 January 2011}}</ref> and featured heavily throughout the season as the team finished in fourth position and [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League|qualified for the Champions League]].\n\nOn 1 July 2011, Villarreal signed Valero on a permanent basis for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/7013644/|title=Valero leaves West Brom|publisher=Sky Sports|date=1 July 2011|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> The former were relegated at the end of [[2011\u201312 La Liga|the campaign]], and it was reported that he was among a number of players expected to leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/es-us/news/2194/main/2012/05/18/3112064/villarreal-giuseppe-rossi-bruno-soriano-cristian-zapata|title=Villarreal: Giuseppe Rossi, Bruno Soriano, Cristian Zapata, Nilmar, Borja Valero y el exilio tras el descenso|trans-title=Villarreal: Giuseppe Rossi, Bruno Soriano, Cristian Zapata, Nilmar, Borja Valero and exile after relegation|publisher=Goal|language=Spanish|date=18 May 2012|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Fiorentina===\nOn 1 August 2012, [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] agreed with Villarreal for the transfer of Valero.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3276/serie-a/2012/08/01/3280436/fiorentina-agree-fee-with-villarreal-to-sign-borja-valero|title=Fiorentina agree fee with Villarreal to sign Borja Valero|publisher=Goal|first=SW|last=Lim|date=1 August 2012|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> The move was confirmed three days later, and he joined the [[Serie A]] side alongside teammate [[Gonzalo Rodr\u00edguez (footballer, born 1984)|Gonzalo Rodr\u00edguez]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.violachannel.tv/breaking-news-detail/items/borja-valero-gonzalo-rodriguez-and-aquilani-to-fiorentina.html|title=Borja Valero, Gonzalo Rodriguez and Aquilani to Fiorentina|publisher=ACF Fiorentina|date=4 August 2012|accessdate=4 August 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229110621/http://en.violachannel.tv/breaking-news-detail/items/borja-valero-gonzalo-rodriguez-and-aquilani-to-fiorentina.html|archive-date=29 December 2016}}</ref> after joining, he said leaving his previous club was not easy and that he still had not come to terms with its relegation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3277/la-liga/2012/08/02/3282021/fiorentina-bound-valero-still-perplexed-by-villarreal|title=Fiorentina-bound Valero still perplexed by Villarreal relegation|publisher=Goal|first=Stefan|last=Coerts|date=2 August 2012|accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nValero made an immediate impact at the ''Viola'', scoring five league goals in 37 games in [[2012\u201313 Serie A|his first season]] and providing 11 [[Assist (association football)|assists]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiorentinanews.com/2012/11/le-nostre-pagelle-ecco-a-voi-il-borja-valero-show-nella-giornata-delle-prime-volte/|title=Le nostre pagelle: Ecco a voi il Borja Valero show nella giornata delle prime volte|trans-title=Our marks: Ladies and gentlemen the Borja Valero show in matchday of first times|publisher=Fiorentina News|language=Italian|date=11 November 2012|accessdate=29 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201215256/http://www.fiorentinanews.com/2012/11/le-nostre-pagelle-ecco-a-voi-il-borja-valero-show-nella-giornata-delle-prime-volte/|archivedate=1 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as the team [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League|qualified to the Europa League]]. He scored his first goal in [[2013\u201314 Serie A|2013\u201314]] on 15 September in a 1\u20131 home draw against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.gazzetta.it/Football/15-09-2013/serie-a-fiorentina-1-1-cagliari-pinilla-replies-to-borja-valero-goal-201164622366.shtml|title=Serie A: Fiorentina 1\u20131 Cagliari \u2013 Pinilla replies to Borja Valero goal|newspaper=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|date=15 September 2013|accessdate=28 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202172522/http://english.gazzetta.it/Football/15-09-2013/serie-a-fiorentina-1-1-cagliari-pinilla-replies-to-borja-valero-goal-201164622366.shtml|archivedate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and, on 2 November, contributed to a 2\u20130 success at [[A.C. Milan|Milan]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/match/119225/milan-vs-fiorentina/report|title=Milan-Fiorentina 0\u20132: Diavolo in crisi, Vargas e Valero non perdonano|trans-title=Milan-Fiorentina 0\u20132: Devils in crisis, Vargas and Valero show no mercy|publisher=Goal|first=Valentino|last=Cesarini|language=Italian|date=2 November 2013|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> subsequently, he was named in Goal.com's ''Serie A Team of the Season''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2014/05/06/4795377/serie-a-team-of-the-season-tevez-toni-head-the-star-cast|title=Serie A Team of the Season: Tevez & Toni head the star cast|publisher=Goal|first=Kris|last=Voakes|date=6 May 2014|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 July 2014, Valero signed a new deal at the [[Stadio Artemio Franchi]] until June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-sg/news/3881/italy/2014/07/16/4961415/valero-signs-new-five-year-deal-with-fiorentina|title=Valero signs new five-year deal with Fiorentina|publisher=Goal|first=Peter|last=Thompson|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Inter Milan===\nOn 10 July 2017, Valero transferred to [[Inter Milan]] on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.violachannel.tv/vc13-dettaglio-breaking/items/id-10-07-2017_17-20-06_borja-valero-passa-allinter.html|title=Borja Valero passa all\u2019Inter|trans-title=Borja Valero goes to Inter|publisher=ACF Fiorentina|language=Italian|date=10 July 2017|access-date=10 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inter.it/en/news/58905/borja-valero-completes-inter-move|title=Borja Valero completes Inter move!|publisher=Inter Milan|date=11 July 2017|access-date=11 July 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his new club on 30 October, in a 2\u20131 away win against [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Hellas Verona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/serie-a/2017-2018/borja-valero-opens-account-for-inter-milan-in-serie-a-win-at-hellas-verona_sto6391104/story.shtml|title=Borja Valero opens account for Inter Milan in Serie A win at Hellas Verona|publisher=Eurosport|date=30 October 2017|access-date=31 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nValero represented the [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain under-19 team]] at the [[2004 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2004 European championships]]. In the final against [[Turkey national under-19 football team|Turkey]] he entered the match as an 85th-minute substitute and, two minutes into stoppage time, scored the only goal of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2004/round=1666/match=79251/index.html|title=Valero ensures victory for Spain|publisher=UEFA|first=Andrew|last=Haslam|date=24 July 2004|accessdate=28 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120715082459/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2004/round=1666/match=79251/index.html|archivedate=15 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 June 2011, Valero made his debut for [[Spain national football team|the full side]], against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]]. He replaced [[David Silva]] in the second half, and assisted [[Fernando Torres]] in the last goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2011/06/04/spain-overpower-experimental-us-side-4-0-romp|title=Spain overpower experimental US side in 4\u20130 romp|publisher=[[Major League Soccer]]|first=Kyle|last=McCarthy|date=4 June 2011|accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2011/06/05/2518430/cazorla-silva-shine-negredo-nets-torres-returns-spain|title=Cazorla & Silva shine, Negredo nets, Torres returns \u2013 Spain extract maximum satisfaction from comfortable USA triumph|publisher=Goal|first=Paul|last=Macdonald|date=5 June 2011|accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nPrimarily a central midfielder, Valero is a talented and creative [[playmaker]], who is best known for his positional sense, vision, technique and passing ability,<ref name=Best>{{cite web|url=https://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/spalletti-still-in-search-of-borja-valero-s-best-position-18709|title=Spalletti still in search of Borja Valero\u2019s best position|publisher=Calcio Mercato|first=Jordan|last=Russell|date=20 December 2017|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/42956/brilliance-borja-valero|title=The brilliance of Borja Valero|publisher=Football Italia|date=18 December 2013|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/borja-valero-shines-fiorentina-downs-udinese/|title=Borja Valero shines as Fiorentina downs Udinese|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]|date=11 February 2017|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref> as well as his leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/serie-a/spalletti-su-icardi-abbiamo-tanti-leader-handanovic-ranocchia-borja-1214836|title=Spalletti su Icardi: \"Abbiamo tanti leader. Handanovic, Ranocchia, Borja\"|trans-title=Spalletti to Icardi: \"We have a lot a leaders. Handanovic, Ranocchia, Borja\"|publisher=Tutto Mercato Web|first=Ivan|last=Cardia|language=Italian|date=16 February 2019|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> A versatile player, he is also capable of playing as a [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker|deep-lying playmaker]], as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] or even as an offensive-minded central midfielder, known as the \"[[Midfielder#Mezzala|mezzala]]\" role in Italian football jargon.<ref name=Best/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/inter-what-s-next-for-borja-valero-13827|title=Inter, what's next for Borja Valero|publisher=Calcio Mercato|date=21 November 2019|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/2017/07/12/borja-valero-eyes-key-role-on-and-off-the-pitch.html|title=Borja Valero eyes key role on and off the pitch|publisher=Inter Milan|date=12 July 2017|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 14 January 2020}}<ref>{{ESPN FC|71702}}</ref><ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/borja-valero-iglesias/19222/|title=Borja Valero|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"3\"|Cup<sup>[[#notes gs1|1]]</sup>\n!colspan=\"3\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"3\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Assists!!Apps!!Goals!!Assists!!Apps!!Goals!!Assists!!Apps!!Goals!!Assists\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]]\n|[[2005\u201306 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2005\u201306]]\n|39||2||\u2013||colspan=\"3\"|\u2014||colspan=\"3\"|\u2014||39||2||\u2014\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Real Madrid Castilla season|2006\u201307]]\n|37||2||\u2013||colsp